2025-10-22-160710_vikk.jpg.webp 576w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_768x768_crop_center-center_82_line/826323/asa-stahl-headshot_2025-10-22-160710_vikk.jpg.webp 768w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_1200x1200_crop_center-center_82_line/826323/asa-stahl-headshot_2025-10-22-160710_vikk.jpg.webp 1200w\"\ndata-sizes=\"auto\"\ntype=\"image/webp\" />\n<img\nclass=\"lazyload rounded-full mr-2\" style=\"height:4rem; width:4rem;\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%27http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%27%20width=%271200%27%20height=%271200%27%20style=%27background:%23CCC%27%20/%3E\"\ndata-srcset=\"https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_200x200_crop_center-center_82_line/826323/asa-stahl-headshot_2025-10-22-160710_vikk.jpg 200w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_576x576_crop_center-center_82_line/826323/asa-stahl-headshot_2025-10-22-160710_vikk.jpg 576w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_768x768_crop_center-center_82_line/826323/asa-stahl-headshot_2025-10-22-160710_vikk.jpg 768w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_1200x1200_crop_center-center_82_line/826323/asa-stahl-headshot_2025-10-22-160710_vikk.jpg 1200w\"\ndata-sizes=\"auto\"\nalt=\"Asa Stahl\" />\n</picture><div><p\nclass=\"mt-0 mb-0 text-xs md:text-sm leading-normal\"><strong>Written by </strong>\n<a\nhref=\"https://www.planetary.org/profiles/asa-stahl\"><strong>Asa Stahl, PhD</strong></a>\n<br>Science Editor, The Planetary Society                                                                                                                                                                            <br>November 19, 2024</p></div></div></header></div></div><div\nclass=\"flex justify-center mx-auto\"><div\nclass=\"container-med w-full px-6\"><p>No matter where you live or how much you know about space, you can spot wonders above you in the night sky. All it takes is a few basic tips to transform the twinkling lights overhead into your window to the wider Universe.</p></div></div><div\nclass=\"flex justify-center mx-auto container-wide w-full px-0 md:px-6 my-12\"><figure\nclass=\"table mx-auto\">\n<a\nhref=\"https://www.planetary.org/space-images/gazing-up-at-the-night-sky\">\n<picture\nclass=\"block\">\n<source\nclass= \"lazyload\" data-srcset=\"https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_576x383_crop_center-center_82_line/gazing-up-at-night-sky.jpg.webp 576w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_768x511_crop_center-center_82_line/gazing-up-at-night-sky.jpg.webp 768w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_1200x799_crop_center-center_82_line/gazing-up-at-night-sky.jpg.webp 1200w\"\nsizes=\"100vw\"\ntype=\"image/webp\" />\n<img\nclass=\"lazyload\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%27http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%27%20width=%271200%27%20height=%27799%27%20style=%27background:%23CCC%27%20/%3E\"\ndata-srcset=\"https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_576x383_crop_center-center_82_line/gazing-up-at-night-sky.jpg 576w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_768x511_crop_center-center_82_line/gazing-up-at-night-sky.jpg 768w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_1200x799_crop_center-center_82_line/gazing-up-at-night-sky.jpg 1200w\"\nsizes=\"100vw\"\nalt=\"Gazing up at the night sky\"/>\n</picture>\n</a><figcaption\nclass=\"px-6 md:px-0 font-light mt-2 mb-0 leading-normal text-base\"><span\nclass=\"text-base font-semibold uppercase my-0\">Gazing up at the night sky</span> A person looking up at the night sky.<span\nclass=\"text-gray-700 ml-2\"><em>Image: ESO/B. Tafreshi (twanight.org)</em></span></figcaption></figure></div><div\nclass=\"flex justify-center mx-auto\"><div\nclass=\"container-med w-full px-6\"><blockquote\nclass=\"bg-gray-200 mb-6 px-6 py-1 font-thin text-xl rounded-lg\"><h2>Sneak peek alert!</h2><p>This article offers content from <a\nhref=\"https://community.planetary.org/spaces/16804490/content\">Stargazing 101</a>, our new in-depth guide on how to explore the night sky. Stargazing 101 is available to all Planetary Society members in our <a\nhref=\"community.planetary.org\">digital community</a>. Everyone from newbies to space nerds is welcome — not a member yet? Join today at <a\nhref=\"https://www.planetary.org/membership\">planetary.org/membership</a>.</p></blockquote></div></div><div\nclass=\"flex justify-center mx-auto\"><div\nclass=\"container-med w-full px-6\"><h2>Planets, stars, and constellations</h2><p>You can spot planets like Jupiter and Saturn with a simple trick: while stars twinkle, planets usually don’t. That means if you see a bright, steady, unmoving light in the sky, it might be one of the Solar System’s more visible planets — probably Venus or Jupiter, if it looks brighter than every star in the sky. If a few stars do outshine your planet, then it’s probably Saturn or Mars instead.&nbsp;</p><p>On the other hand, if your light is moving steadily across the sky but still doesn’t twinkle, you might be looking at a satellite. A light that blinks is probably an airplane, and a light that streaks across the sky in a blink of an eye is probably a meteor.&nbsp;</p><p>Once you can pick out worlds, your next step might be spotting constellations and asterisms. An asterism is just what most people think of as a constellation: a recognizable pattern of lights in the sky, like the Big Dipper. Officially, according to the International Astronomical Union (IAU), a constellation is a little bit different. Unlike asterisms, constellations define areas of the sky, with the entire sky divided up into these different regions. Most constellations are defined around popular asterisms, so they’re easy to confuse — for instance, the constellation Ursa Major frames the Big Dipper asterism.&nbsp;</p></div></div><div\nclass=\"flex justify-center mx-auto container-med w-full px-0 sm:px-6 my-12\"><figure\nclass=\"table mx-auto\">\n<a\nhref=\"https://www.planetary.org/space-images/the-pleiades-in-the-night-sky\">\n<picture\nclass=\"block\">\n<source\nclass= \"lazyload\" data-srcset=\"https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_576x324_crop_center-center_82_line/778023/pleiades-night-sky.jpg.webp 576w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_768x432_crop_center-center_82_line/778023/pleiades-night-sky.jpg.webp 768w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_1200x675_crop_center-center_82_line/778023/pleiades-night-sky.jpg.webp 1200w\"\nsizes=\"100vw\"\ntype=\"image/webp\" />\n<img\nclass=\"lazyload\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%27http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%27%20width=%271200%27%20height=%27675%27%20style=%27background:%23CCC%27%20/%3E\"\ndata-srcset=\"https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_576x324_crop_center-center_82_line/778023/pleiades-night-sky.jpg 576w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_768x432_crop_center-center_82_line/778023/pleiades-night-sky.jpg 768w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_1200x675_crop_center-center_82_line/778023/pleiades-night-sky.jpg 1200w\"\nsizes=\"100vw\"\nalt=\"The Pleiades in the night sky\"/>\n</picture>\n</a><figcaption\nclass=\"px-6 sm:px-0 font-light mt-2 mb-0 leading-normal text-base\"><span\nclass=\"text-base font-semibold uppercase my-0\">The Pleiades in the night sky</span> The Pleiades star cluster in the night sky.<span\nclass=\"text-gray-700 ml-2\"><em>Image: ESA / Hubble (M. Kornmesser &amp; L. L. Christensen)</em></span></figcaption></figure></div><div\nclass=\"flex justify-center mx-auto\"><div\nclass=\"container-med w-full px-6\"><p>The IAU outlines 88 official constellations spanning the entire sky, but many cultures describe their own constellations as various patterns of stars. After all, humankind has traced shapes out of the stars for thousands of years, using them to frame stories, tell time, navigate, and make sense of the natural world.&nbsp;</p><p>To learn the constellations, you can&nbsp;use a star chart or app to identify what’s overhead. Start with constellations you can rely on as bright landmarks in different seasons, like Orion and Ursa Major in the Northern Hemisphere, or Crux in the Southern Hemisphere. As you learn more, you can gradually wean yourself off your reference guide.</p></div></div><div\nclass=\"flex justify-center mx-auto container-wide w-full px-0 md:px-6 my-12\"><figure\nclass=\"table mx-auto\">\n<a\nhref=\"https://www.planetary.org/space-images/the-bortle-scale\">\n<picture\nclass=\"block\">\n<source\nclass= \"lazyload\" data-srcset=\"https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_576x324_crop_center-center_82_line/bortle-scale.jpg.webp 576w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_768x432_crop_center-center_82_line/bortle-scale.jpg.webp 768w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_1200x675_crop_center-center_82_line/bortle-scale.jpg.webp 1200w\"\nsizes=\"100vw\"\ntype=\"image/webp\" />\n<img\nclass=\"lazyload\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%27http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%27%20width=%271200%27%20height=%27675%27%20style=%27background:%23CCC%27%20/%3E\"\ndata-srcset=\"https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_576x324_crop_center-center_82_line/bortle-scale.jpg 576w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_768x432_crop_center-center_82_line/bortle-scale.jpg 768w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_1200x675_crop_center-center_82_line/bortle-scale.jpg 1200w\"\nsizes=\"100vw\"\nalt=\"The Bortle scale\"/>\n</picture>\n</a><figcaption\nclass=\"px-6 md:px-0 font-light mt-2 mb-0 leading-normal text-base\"><span\nclass=\"text-base font-semibold uppercase my-0\">The Bortle scale</span> A depiction of the Bortle scale and how it corresponds to different levels of light pollution.<span\nclass=\"text-gray-700 ml-2\"><em>Image: ESO/P. Horálek, M. Wallner</em></span></figcaption></figure></div><div\nclass=\"flex justify-center mx-auto\"><div\nclass=\"container-med w-full px-6\"><h2>The right time and place</h2><p>A lot of astronomy comes down to knowing where and when to stargaze. Since lights on the ground will make the sky brighter and wash out dimmer sights overhead — a phenomenon known as light pollution<i>&nbsp;</i>— the&nbsp;<a\nhref=\"https://www.lightpollutionmap.info/\">farther away</a> you can be from a city, the better.&nbsp;</p><p>No matter where you are, give yourself time for your eyes to adjust to the dark. It takes most people about half an hour to fully adapt to night vision, but only a moment’s glance at a bright light to completely reset their sensitivity to light. So, be careful! If you need to see what’s around you on Earth, use dim red lights, which will affect your night vision less.</p><p>When you stargaze is just as important as where you stargaze. Pay attention to the&nbsp;<a\nhref=\"https://www.planetary.org/articles/the-phases-of-the-moon-explained\">phase of the Moon</a>: a near-full Moon will drastically brighten the sky and diminish what you’ll be able to see. Bad weather can also hurt your chances of seeing anything, so check the forecast before you head out. Finally, keep an ear to the ground to learn if anything particularly impressive is going to be visible soon.&nbsp;The Planetary Society’s weekly email newsletter&nbsp;<a\nhref=\"https://www.planetary.org/articles?keywords=the-downlink\">The Downlink</a> will keep you updated on&nbsp;<a\nhref=\"https://www.planetary.org/night-sky/night-sky-what-to-see-this-month\">night sky highlights</a>.&nbsp;</p></div></div><div\nclass=\"flex justify-center mx-auto container-med w-full px-0 sm:px-6 my-12\"><figure\nclass=\"table mx-auto\">\n<a\nhref=\"https://www.planetary.org/space-images/the-milky-way-from-the-vlt\">\n<picture\nclass=\"block\">\n<source\nclass= \"lazyload\" data-srcset=\"https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_1200x799_crop_center-center_82_line/milky-way-above-eso.jpg.webp 1200w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_768x511_crop_center-center_82_line/milky-way-above-eso.jpg.webp 768w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_576x383_crop_center-center_82_line/milky-way-above-eso.jpg.webp 576w\"\nsizes=\"100vw\"\ntype=\"image/webp\" />\n<img\nclass=\"lazyload\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=%27http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%27%20width=%271200%27%20height=%27799%27%20style=%27background:%23CCC%27%20/%3E\"\ndata-srcset=\"https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_1200x799_crop_center-center_82_line/milky-way-above-eso.jpg 1200w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_768x511_crop_center-center_82_line/milky-way-above-eso.jpg 768w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_576x383_crop_center-center_82_line/milky-way-above-eso.jpg 576w\"\nsizes=\"100vw\"\nalt=\"The Milky Way from the VLT\"/>\n</picture>\n</a><figcaption\nclass=\"px-6 sm:px-0 font-light mt-2 mb-0 leading-normal text-base\"><span\nclass=\"text-base font-semibold uppercase my-0\">The Milky Way from the VLT</span> The Milky Way in the night sky, as seen from the European Southern Observatory's Very Large Telescope.<span\nclass=\"text-gray-700 ml-2\"><em>Image: ESO/Luis Calçada/Herbert Zodet</em></span></figcaption></figure></div><div\nclass=\"flex justify-center mx-auto\"><div\nclass=\"container-med w-full px-6\"><h2>No telescope, no problem</h2><p>You don’t need a telescope to stargaze. Though a telescope will help you spot dimmer objects, there are plenty of bright sights to see, like the Moon, the&nbsp;<a\nhref=\"https://www.planetary.org/articles/how-to-spot-the-iss\">International Space Station</a>, and many planets and stars. Some things, like&nbsp;<a\nhref=\"https://www.planetary.org/articles/your-guide-meteor-shower\">meteor showers</a> and the Milky Way, might actually be easier to appreciate with your naked eye. The brightest features of the night sky also tend to have rich histories and mythologies.&nbsp;</p><p>If you do choose to stargaze through a telescope, it will unlock a whole new way to explore the Universe. A decent-sized telescope will allow you to see details of star clusters, nebulae, galaxies, the Moon, and planets, like Saturn’s rings and Jupiter’s Great Red Spot. It’s possible to buy a worthwhile beginner telescope for&nbsp;<a\nhref=\"https://www.planetary.org/articles/how-to-pick-the-perfect-beginner-telescope\">as low as $150</a> — not cheap, but not astronomical, either (sorry). And for those who want to dip a toe in before they decide to buy a&nbsp;telescope, binoculars offer a great first step. Even better, consider attending a&nbsp;<a\nhref=\"http://www.skyandtelescope.org/astronomy-clubs-organizations/\">local astronomy club</a> to check out different telescopes and see what they’re like.</p><h2>Read our full guide!</h2><p>Learn more about how to explore the night sky with our <a\nhref=\"https://community.planetary.org/spaces/16804490/content\">new in-depth guide</a> on how to see the best possible views and help others fall in love with stargazing. Now available to all Planetary Society members in our digital community. Everyone from newbies to space nerds is welcome! Not a member yet? Join today at <a\nhref=\"https://www.planetary.org/membership\">planetary.org/membership</a>.&nbsp;</p></div></div><div\nclass=\"flex justify-center mx-auto\"><div\nclass=\"container-med w-full px-6 text-center\"><div\nclass=\"bg-gray-200 mb-10 text-2xl text-center\"><div\nclass=\"text-center bg-cover bg-center mb-0 py-8 flex justify-center items-center\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Artist illustration of Kepler-62f\" style=\"background-image: url(https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/sites/planetary/images/cta-orion-nebula-jwst.jpg); background-position: 100% 50%; min-height: 180px;\"></div><div\nclass=\"p-6\"><h3 class=\"mt-2 mb-2 uppercase\">Support our core enterprises</h3><p\nclass=\"mt-4\">Your gift today will go far to help us close out the year strong and keep up our momentum in 2026.</p>\n<a\nclass=\"btn btn-orange px-6 py-2 text-lg mb-4\" href=\"https://connect.planetary.org/64?s_cid=2025yearend&s_pkgsrc=2025yearend-unsol&s_src=2025yearend&s_subsrc=card\">Donate</a></div></div></div></div><footer\nclass=\"flex justify-center mx-auto\"><div\nclass=\"container-med w-full px-6\"><div\nclass=\"border-t border-gre-lightery pt-2 my-9\"><div\nclass=\"m-b-10\" style=\"text-indent:-1.7rem; margin-left:2.8rem;\"><p\nclass=\"text-base mb-2\"><span\nclass=\"icon-book\" aria-hidden=\"true\" role=\"presentation\"></span> Read more: <a\nhref=\"/articles?keywords=earths-night-sky\" class=\"text-planetary-blue hover:border-b-2 hover:border-planetary-blue\"> Earth&#039;s night sky</a>, <a\nhref=\"/articles?keywords=earth-moon-system\" class=\"text-planetary-blue hover:border-b-2 hover:border-planetary-blue\"> The Earth-Moon system</a>, <a\nhref=\"/articles?keywords=space-places\" class=\"text-planetary-blue hover:border-b-2 hover:border-planetary-blue\"> Worlds</a></p><p\nclass=\"text-base mt-2 mb-8\"><span\nclass=\"icon-location\" aria-hidden=\"true\" role=\"presentation\"></span> You are here: <a\nhref=\"/\" class=\"text-planetary-blue hover:border-b-2 hover:border-planetary-blue\">Home</a> &gt; <a\nhref=\"/articles/\" class=\"text-planetary-blue hover:border-b-2 hover:border-planetary-blue\">Articles</a></p></div><div\nclass=\"bg-gray-200 p-6 mb-10 \"><div\nclass=\"flex items-top md:items-center \">\n<picture\nclass=\"flex-none rounded-full h-24 w-24 mr-6\">\n<source\ndata-srcset=\"https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_200x200_crop_center-center_82_line/826323/asa-stahl-headshot_2025-10-22-160710_vikk.jpg.webp 200w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_576x576_crop_center-center_82_line/826323/asa-stahl-headshot_2025-10-22-160710_vikk.jpg.webp 576w, https://planetary.s3.amazonaws.com/web/assets/pictures/_768x768_cro